>
> This lower level of efficiency is a common problem with budget rebuilds.
>
> I saw a rebuild from another budget rebuilder (JCS) and it only got 12mpg at 
> 1300 miles after installation. The rebuilder assured the owner the numbers 
> would improve as the engine broke in but they didn't. After a lot of 
> expensive to install CDI etc the mileage only improved to 14mpg.
>
  Compression numbers were in the low 120's iirc. I did a leak down test on it
  one day and every cylinder had a poor seal. I told the owner it would never
  get average bus mileage until it was rebuilt properly. I couldn't tell how
  good the ring seal was because so much air was escaping thru the valves.

> Dave, what is the gas mileage with your engine?
>
>
> I think they are following Boston Bob's advice:
>
> http://www.bostonengine.com/articles/todaysfuels.html
>

  So, I wonder what kind of compression ratio that George ended up with?
>
> I've seen them as low as 110psi before first run. If you load up a cylinder 
> with oil just like you find after assembly but before firing you should see 
> abnormally high readings but when they are this low to begin with, the engine 
> will never run as well as the factory build did.
